# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: architecture-patterns
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] The *architecture* of a software system is a metaphor, analogous to the architecture of a building.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] It functions as the blueprints for the system and the development project, which project management can later use to extrapolate the tasks necessary to be executed by the teams and people involved.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture is about making fundamental structural choices that are costly to change once implemented.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture choices include specific structural options from possibilities in the design of the software.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] "Architectural Kata" is a teamwork which can be used to produce an architectural solution that fits the needs.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Each team extracts and prioritizes architectural characteristics (aka non functional requirements) then models the components accordingly.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] The team can use C4 Model which is a flexible method to model the architecture just enough.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Note that synchronous communication between architectural components, entangles them and they must share the same architectural characteristics.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Documenting software architecture facilitates communication between stakeholders, captures early decisions about the high-level design, and allows the reuse of design components between projects.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture design is commonly juxtaposed with software application design.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architectures can be categorized into two main types: monolith and distributed architecture, each having its own subcategories.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture tends to become more complex over time.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architects should use "fitness functions" to continuously keep the architecture in check.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] There is no sharp distinction between software architecture versus design and requirements engineering (see Related fields below).
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] They are all part of a "chain of intentionality" from high-level intentions to low-level details.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] The following architectural anti-patterns can arise when architects make decisions.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] These anti-patterns often follow a progressive sequence, where resolving one may lead to the emergence of another.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture is an "intellectually graspable" abstraction of a complex system.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] The comparison between software design and (civil) architecture was first drawn in the late 1960s, but the term "software architecture" did not see widespread usage until the 1990s.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] The field of computer science had encountered problems associated with complexity since its formation.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Earlier problems of complexity were solved by developers by choosing the right data structures, developing algorithms, and by applying the concept of separation of concerns.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Although the term "software architecture" is relatively new to the industry, the fundamental principles of the field have been applied sporadically by software engineering pioneers since the mid-1980s.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Early attempts to capture and explain software architecture of a system were imprecise and disorganized, often characterized by a set of box-and-line diagrams.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture as a concept has its origins in the research of Edsger Dijkstra in 1968 and David Parnas in the early 1970s.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] These scientists emphasized that the structure of a software system matters and getting the structure right is critical.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] During the 1990s there was a concerted effort to define and codify fundamental aspects of the discipline, with research work concentrating on architectural styles (patterns), architecture description languages, architecture documentation, and formal methods.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Research institutions have played a prominent role in furthering software architecture as a discipline.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Mary Shaw and David Garlan of Carnegie Mellon wrote a book titled *Software Architecture: Perspectives on an Emerging Discipline* in 1996, which promoted software architecture concepts such as components, connectors, and styles.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] The University of California, Irvine's Institute for Software Research's efforts in software architecture research is directed primarily in architectural styles, architecture description languages, and dynamic architectures.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] IEEE 1471-2000, "Recommended Practice for Architecture Description of Software-Intensive Systems", was the first formal standard in the area of software architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] In November 2011, IEEE 1471–2000 was superseded by ISO/IEC/IEEE 42010:2011, "Systems and software engineering – Architecture description" (jointly published by IEEE and ISO).
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] This reflects the relationship between software architecture, enterprise architecture and solution architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Making architectural decisions involves collecting sufficient relevant information, providing justification for the decision, documenting the decision and its rationale, and communicating it effectively to the appropriate stakeholders.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] It's software architect's responsibility to match architectural characteristics (aka non-functional requirements) with business requirements.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] There are four core activities in software architecture design.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] These core architecture activities are performed iteratively and at different stages of the initial software development life-cycle, as well as over the evolution of a system.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] The outputs of the analysis activity are those requirements that have a measurable impact on a software system's architecture, called architecturally significant requirements.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Architecture requires critical supporting activities.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] These supporting activities take place throughout the core software architecture process.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] They include knowledge management and communication, design reasoning and decision-making, and documentation.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture supporting activities are carried out during core software architecture activities.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] These supporting activities assist a software architect to carry out analysis, synthesis, evaluation, and evolution.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] For instance, an architect has to gather knowledge, make decisions, and document during the analysis phase.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture inherently deals with uncertainties, and the size of architectural components can significantly influence a system's outcomes, both positively and negatively.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Neal Ford and Mark Richards propose an iterative approach to address the challenge of identifying and right-sizing components.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] This method emphasizes continuous refinement as teams develop a more nuanced understanding of system behavior and requirements.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] This cycle serves as a general framework and can be adapted to different domains.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] There are also concerns that software architecture leads to too much big design up front, especially among proponents of agile software development.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] A number of methods have been developed to balance the trade-offs of up-front design and agility, including the agile method DSDM which mandates a "Foundations" phase during which "just enough" architectural foundations are laid.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] *IEEE Software* devoted a special issue to the interaction between agility and architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture erosion refers to a gradual gap between the intended and implemented architecture of a software system over time.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] The phenomenon of software architecture erosion was initially brought to light in 1992 by Perry and Wolf alongside their definition of software architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture erosion may occur in each stage of the software development life cycle and has varying impacts on the development speed and the cost of maintenance.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture erosion occurs due to various reasons, such as *architectural violations*, *the accumulation of technical debt*, and *knowledge vaporization*.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] A famous case of architecture erosion is the failure of Mozilla Web browser.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Mozilla is an application created by Netscape with a complex codebase that became harder to maintain due to continuous changes.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Due to initial poor design and growing architecture erosion, Netscape spent two years redeveloping the Mozilla Web browser, demonstrating the importance of proactive architecture management to prevent costly repairs and project delays.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Architecture erosion can decrease software performance, substantially increase evolutionary costs, and degrade software quality.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Various approaches and tools have been proposed to detect architecture erosion.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] These approaches are primarily classified into four categories: consistency-based, evolution-based, defect-based, and decision-based approaches.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] For instance, automated architecture conformance checks, static code analysis tools, and refactoring techniques help identify and mitigate erosion early.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Besides, the measures used to address architecture erosion contain two main types: preventative and remedial measures.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Preventative measures include enforcing architectural rules, regular code reviews, and automated testing, while remedial measures involve refactoring, redesign, and documentation updates.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Software architecture recovery (or reconstruction, or reverse engineering) includes the methods, techniques, and processes to uncover a software system's architecture from available information, including its implementation and documentation.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Architecture recovery is often necessary to make informed decisions in the face of obsolete or out-of-date documentation and architecture erosion: implementation and maintenance decisions diverging from the envisioned architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Practices exist to recover software architecture as static program analysis.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] This is a part of the subjects covered by the software intelligence practice.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Architecture is design but not all design is architectural.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] In practice, the architect is the one who draws the line between software architecture (architectural design) and detailed design (non-architectural design).
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] There are no rules or guidelines that fit all cases, although there have been attempts to formalize the distinction.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] For example, the client–server style is architectural (strategic) because a program that is built on this principle can be expanded into a program that is not client–server—for example, by adding peer-to-peer nodes.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Requirements engineering and software architecture can be seen as complementary approaches: while software architecture targets the 'solution space' or the 'how', requirements engineering addresses the 'problem space' or the 'what'.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Requirements engineering entails the elicitation, negotiation, specification, validation, documentation, and management of requirements.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Both requirements engineering and software architecture revolve around stakeholder concerns, needs, and wishes.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] In short, required behavior impacts solution architecture, which in turn may introduce new requirements.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Approaches such as the Twin Peaks model aim to exploit the synergistic relation between requirements and architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Serverless architecture is a cloud computing paradigm that is often misunderstood as being server-free.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] It essentially shifts server management responsibilities from developers to cloud service providers.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] This allows businesses to run their backend code on cloud infrastructure, eliminating the need for physical server management.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] The event-driven approach of serverless architecture relies on small, task-specific functions that are executed on-demand.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] These functions are known as Function as a Service (FaaS), and they offer cost-efficiency through a pay-as-you-go billing model and dynamic resource scaling based on application demand.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] The main concern addressed by the systems architecture is then the integration of software and hardware in a complete, correctly working device.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] is to "translate business vision and strategy into effective enterprise".
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] , usually distinguish between different enterprise architecture layers.
[src:architecture-patterns/architectural-pattern] Enterprise architecture addresses among others the alignment between these layers, usually in a top-down approach.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] In **modern enterprise systems**, increasing architectural complexity has introduced significant challenges related to scalability, maintainability, and runtime performance.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] Implementations of **Command Query Responsibility Segregation (CQRS)** and event-driven designs frequently integrate core business logic with cross-cutting concerns such as logging, retry policies, and audit propagation.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] This combination can lead to tightly coupled components, reducing modularity and complicating long-term evolution.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] Modern CQRS frameworks aim to decouple these operational aspects from domain logic to improve system adaptability.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] Drawing on established design principles—such as the Chain of Responsibility and Strategy patterns—alongside declarative programming paradigms, CQRS models command processing as a functional pipeline P .
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] Each processing stage $s\in S$ (for example, routing, middleware execution, handler invocation, or post-processing) is coordinated through dynamically extensible interceptor chains I .
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] This architectural approach is intended to provide predictable latency, high throughput, strong type safety, and reliable idempotency characteristics, making it suitable for resilient large-scale distributed applications.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] In information technology, **Command Query Responsibility Segregation** (CQRS) is a software architecture that extends the idea behind command–query separation (CQS) to the level of services.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] Such a system will have separate interfaces to send queries and to send commands.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] As in CQS, fulfilling a query request will only retrieve data and will not modify the state of the system (with some exceptions like logging access), while fulfilling a command request will modify the state of the system.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] Many systems push the segregation to the data models used by the system.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] The models used to process queries are usually called *read models* and the models used to process commands *write models*.
[src:architecture-patterns/command-query-responsibility-segregation] Although its origin is usually attributed to Greg Young in 2010, everything indicates that the precursor of CQRS was Udi Dahan who in August 2008 published on his blog a training course that aimed to apply CQRS together with SOA and in more detail in December 2009 in the article Clarified CQRS.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] An **enterprise service bus** (**ESB**) implements a communication system between mutually interacting software applications in a service-oriented architecture (SOA).
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] It represents a software architecture for distributed computing, and is a special variant of the more general client-server model, wherein any application may behave as server or client.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] ESB promotes agility and flexibility with regard to high-level protocol communication between applications.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] Its primary use is in enterprise application integration (EAI) of heterogeneous and complex service landscapes.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] The concept of the enterprise service bus is analogous to the bus concept found in computer hardware architecture combined with the modular and concurrent design of high-performance computer operating systems.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] ESB is also a common implementation pattern for service-oriented architecture, including the intrinsically adopted network design of the World Wide Web.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] No global standards exist for enterprise service bus concepts or implementations.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] Most providers of message-oriented middleware have adopted the enterprise service bus concept as *de facto* standard for a service-oriented architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] The implementations of ESB use event-driven and standards-based message-oriented middleware in combination with message queues as technology frameworks.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] However, some software manufacturers relabel existing middleware and communication solutions as ESB without adopting the crucial aspect of a bus concept.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] An ESB applies the design concept of modern operating systems to independent services running within networks of disparate and independent computers.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] Like concurrent operating systems, an ESB provides commodity services in addition to adoption, translation and routing of client requests to appropriate answering services.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] The first published usage of the term "enterprise service bus" is attributed to Roy W.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] Schulte from the Gartner Group 2002 and the book *The Enterprise Service Bus* by David Chappell.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] Roma was first sold in 1998 making it the first commercial ESB in the market, but that Sonic's product from 2002 was also one of the early ESBs on the market.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] The ESB is implemented in software that operates between the business applications, and enables communication among them.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] Ideally, the ESB should be able to replace all direct contact with the applications on the bus, so that all communication takes place via the ESB.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] To achieve this objective, the ESB must encapsulate the functionality offered by its component applications in a meaningful way.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] This typically occurs through the use of an enterprise message model.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] The message model defines a standard set of messages that the ESB transmits and receives.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] When the ESB receives a message, it routes the message to the appropriate application.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] Often, because that application evolved without the same message model, the ESB has to transform the message into a format that the application can interpret.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] A software adapter fulfills the task of effecting these transformations, analogously to a physical adapter.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] ESBs rely on accurately constructing the enterprise message model and properly designing the functionality offered by applications.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] If the message model does not completely encapsulate the application functionality, then other applications that desire that functionality may have to bypass the bus, and invoke the mismatched applications directly.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] Doing so violates the principles of the ESB model, and negates many of the advantages of using this architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] The beauty of the ESB lies in its platform-agnostic nature and the ability to integrate with anything at any condition.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] It is important that Application Lifecycle Management vendors truly apply all the ESB capabilities in their integration products while adopting SOA.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] Therefore, the challenges and opportunities for EAI vendors are to provide an integration solution that is low-cost, easily configurable, intuitive, user-friendly, and open to any tools customers choose.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] ¹ *Some do not regard process choreography as an ESB function.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] These solutions often focus on low-level ESB functions, such as connectivity, routing and transformation, and require coding or scripting to implement orchestration.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] If the message broker, the ESB software, translates a message from one format to another, then as with any translation, there is the issue of semantics of the message.
[src:architecture-patterns/enterprise-service-bus] For the known corner cases the number of tests that cover all corner cases increases exponentially with every application that is connected to the ESB, because every ESB-connected application must be tested against every other application that is connected to the ESB.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] An *event* can be defined as "a significant change in state".
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] For example, when a consumer purchases a car, the car's state changes from "for sale" to "sold".
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] A car dealer's system architecture may treat this state change as an event whose occurrence can be made known to other applications within the architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] From a formal perspective, what is produced, published, propagated, detected or consumed is a (typically asynchronous) message called the event notification, and not the event itself, which is the state change that triggered the message emission.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] However, the term *event* is often used metonymically to denote the notification message itself, which may lead to some confusion.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This is due to Event-driven architectures often being designed atop **message-driven architectures**, where such a communication pattern requires one of the inputs to be text-only, the message, to differentiate how each communication should be handled.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This architectural pattern may be applied by the design and implementation of applications and systems that transmit events among loosely coupled software components and services.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] An event-driven system typically consists of event emitters (or agents), event consumers (or sinks), and event channels.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Emitters have the responsibility to detect, gather, and transfer events.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] An Event Emitter does not know the consumers of the event, it does not even know if a consumer exists, and in case it exists, it does not know how the event is used or further processed.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Sinks have the responsibility of applying a reaction as soon as an event is presented.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The reaction might or might not be completely provided by the sink itself.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] For instance, the sink might just have the responsibility to filter, transform and forward the event to another component or it might provide a self-contained reaction to such an event.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Event channels are conduits in which events are transmitted from event emitters to event consumers.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The knowledge of the correct distribution of events is exclusively present within the event channel.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The physical implementation of event channels can be based on traditional components such as message-oriented middleware or point-to-point communication which might require a more appropriate transactional executive framework.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Building systems around an event-driven architecture simplifies horizontal scalability in distributed computing models and makes them more resilient to failure.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This is because application state can be copied across multiple parallel snapshots for high-availability.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] New events can be initiated anywhere, but more importantly propagate across the network of data stores updating each as they arrive.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Adding extra nodes becomes trivial as well: you can simply take a copy of the application state, feed it a stream of events and run with it.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Event-driven architecture can complement service-oriented architecture (SOA) because services can be activated by triggers fired on incoming events.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This paradigm is particularly useful whenever the sink does not provide any self-contained executive.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] SOA 2.0 evolves the implications SOA and EDA architectures provide to a richer, more robust level by leveraging previously unknown causal relationships to form a new event pattern.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This new business intelligence pattern triggers further autonomous human or automated processing that adds exponential value to the enterprise by injecting value-added information into the recognized pattern which could not have been achieved previously.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Event driven architecture has two primary topologies.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] With “broker topology”, components broadcast events to the entire system without any orchestrator.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This topology provides higher performance and scalability.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] With “mediator topology”, there is a central orchestrator which controls workflow of events.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This topology provides better control and error handling capabilities.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] You can also use a hybrid model and combine these two topologies.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] There are different types of events in EDA, and opinions on their classification may vary.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Domain events signify important occurrences within a specific business domain.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] These events are restricted to a bounded context and are vital for preserving business logic.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Typically, domain events have lighter payloads, containing only the necessary information for processing.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This is because event listeners are generally within the same service, where their requirements are more clearly understood.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] On the other hand, integration events serve to communicate changes across different bounded contexts.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] They are crucial for ensuring data consistency throughout the entire system.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Integration events tend to have more complex payloads with additional attributes, as the needs of potential listeners can differ significantly.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This often leads to a more thorough approach to communication, resulting in overcommunication to ensure that all relevant information is effectively shared.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] An event can be made of two parts, the event header and the event body also known as event payload.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The event header might include information such as event name, time stamp for the event, and type of event.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The event payload provides the details of the state change detected.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] An event body should not be confused with the pattern or the logic that may be applied in reaction to the occurrence of the event itself.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This method involves including only keys or IDs, allowing consumers to fetch the required data from external data sources, such as databases.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] While this approach is less scalable and slower due to the need for database queries, it minimizes bandwidth usage and reduces coupling issues.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] These methods represent two ends of a spectrum rather than binary choices.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Architects must carefully size the event payloads to meet the specific needs of event consumers.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] In event driven architectures, event evolution poses challenges, such as managing inconsistent event schemas across services and ensuring compatibility during gradual system updates.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Event evolution strategies in event-driven architectures (EDA) can ensure that systems can handle changes to events without disruption.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] These strategies can include versioning events, such as semantic versioning or schema evolution, to maintain backward and forward compatibility.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Adapters can translate events between old and new formats, ensuring consistent processing across components.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] These techniques can enable systems to evolve while remaining compatible and reliable in complex, distributed environments.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The first logical layer is the event producer, which senses a fact and represents that fact as an event message.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] As an example, an event producer could be an email client, an E-commerce system, a monitoring agent or some type of physical sensor.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Converting the data collected from such a diverse set of data sources to a single standardized form of data for evaluation is a significant task in the design and implementation of this first logical layer.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] However, considering that an event is a strongly declarative frame, any informational operations can be easily applied, thus eliminating the need for a high level of standardization.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] An event channel is a mechanism of propagating the information collected from an event generator to the event engine or sink.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This could be a TCP/IP connection, or any type of an input file (flat, XML format, e-mail, etc.).
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Several event channels can be opened at the same time.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Usually, because the event processing engine has to process them in near real time, the event channels will be read asynchronously.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The events are stored in a queue, waiting to be processed later by the event processing engine.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The event processing engine is the logical layer responsible for identifying an event, and then selecting and executing the appropriate reaction.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] It can also trigger a number of assertions.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] For example, if the event that comes into the event processing engine is a product ID low in stock, this may trigger reactions such as “Order product ID” and “Notify personnel”.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This is the logical layer where the consequences of the event are shown.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This can be done in many different ways and forms; e.g., an email is sent to someone and an application may display some kind of warning on the screen.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Depending on the level of automation provided by the sink (event processing engine) the downstream activity might not be required.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] There are three general styles of event processing: simple, stream, and complex.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The three styles are often used together in a mature event-driven architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Simple event processing concerns events that are directly related to specific, measurable changes of condition.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] In simple event processing, a notable event happens which initiates downstream action(s).
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Simple event processing is commonly used to drive the real-time flow of work, thereby reducing lag time and cost.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] For example, simple events can be created by a sensor detecting changes in tire pressures or ambient temperature.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The car's tire incorrect pressure will generate a simple event from the sensor that will trigger a yellow light advising the driver about the state of a tire.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] In event stream processing (ESP), both ordinary and notable events happen.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Ordinary events (orders, RFID transmissions) are screened for notability and streamed to information subscribers.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Event stream processing is commonly used to drive the real-time flow of information in and around the enterprise, which enables in-time decision making.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Complex event processing (CEP) allows patterns of simple and ordinary events to be considered to infer that a complex event has occurred.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Complex event processing evaluates a confluence of events and then takes action.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The events (notable or ordinary) may cross event types and occur over a long period of time.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The event correlation may be causal, temporal, or spatial.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] CEP requires the employment of sophisticated event interpreters, event pattern definition and matching, and correlation techniques.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] CEP is commonly used to detect and respond to business anomalies, threats, and opportunities.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Online event processing (OLEP) uses asynchronous distributed event logs to process complex events and manage persistent data.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] OLEP allows reliably composing related events of a complex scenario across heterogeneous systems.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] It thereby enables very flexible distribution patterns with high scalability and offers strong consistency.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] However, it cannot guarantee upper bounds on processing time.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] An event-driven architecture is extremely loosely coupled and well distributed.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The great distribution of this architecture exists because an event can be almost anything and exist almost anywhere.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The architecture is extremely loosely coupled because the event itself doesn't know about the consequences of its cause. e.g.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] If we have an alarm system that records information when the front door opens, the door itself doesn't know that the alarm system will add information when the door opens, just that the door has been opened.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Event-driven architectures have loose coupling within space, time and synchronization, providing a scalable infrastructure for information exchange and distributed workflows.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] However, event-architectures are tightly coupled, via event subscriptions and patterns, to the semantics of the underlying event schema and values.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] The high degree of semantic heterogeneity of events in large and open deployments such as smart cities and the sensor web makes it difficult to develop and maintain event-based systems.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] In order to address semantic coupling within event-based systems the use of approximate semantic matching of events is an active area of research.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Event driven architecture is susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Finding the right balance in the number of events can be quite difficult.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Generating too many detailed events can overwhelm the system, making it hard to analyze the overall event flow effectively.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This challenge becomes even greater when rollbacks are required.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Conversely, if events are overly consolidated, it can lead to unnecessary processing and responses from event consumers.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] To achieve an optimal balance, Mark Richards recommends to consider the impact of each event and whether consumers need to review the event payloads to determine their actions.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] For instance, in a compliance check scenario, it may be adequate to publish just two types of events: compliant and non-compliant.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] This method ensures that each event is only processed by the relevant consumers, reducing unnecessary workload.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] One of the challenges of using event driven architecture is error handling.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] One way to address this issue is to use a separate error-handler processor.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] So, when the event consumer experiences an error, it immediately and asynchronously sends the erroneous event to the error-handler processor and moves on.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Error-handler processor tries to fix the error and sends the event back to the original channel.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] But if the error-handler processor fails, then it can send the erroneous event to an administrator for further inspection.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Note that if you use an error-handler processor, erroneous events will be processed out of sequence when they are resubmitted.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] Another challenge of using event driven architecture is data loss.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] If any of the components crashes before successfully processing and handing over the event to its next component, then the event is dropped and never makes it into the final destination.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] To minimize the chance of data loss, you can persist in-transit events and remove / dequeue the events only when the next component has acknowledged the receipt of the event.
[src:architecture-patterns/event-driven-architecture] These features are usually known as "client acknowledge mode" and "last participant support".
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] The **hexagonal architecture**, or **ports and adapters architecture**, is an architectural style used in software design.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] It aims at creating loosely coupled application components that can be easily connected to their software environment by means of ports and adapters.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] This makes components exchangeable at any level and facilitates test automation.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] The hexagonal architecture was invented by Alistair Cockburn in an attempt to avoid known structural pitfalls in object-oriented software design, such as undesired dependencies between layers and contamination of user interface code with business logic.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] It was discussed at first on the Portland Pattern Repository wiki; in 2005 Cockburn renamed it "Ports and adapters".
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] In April 2024, Cockburn published a comprehensive book on the subject, coauthored with Juan Manuel Garrido de Paz.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] The term "hexagonal" comes from the graphical conventions that shows the application component like a hexagonal cell.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] The purpose was not to suggest that there would be six borders/ports, but to leave enough space to represent the different interfaces needed between the component and the external world.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] The hexagonal architecture divides a system into several loosely-coupled interchangeable components, such as the application core, the database, the user interface, test scripts and interfaces with other systems.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] This approach is an alternative to the traditional layered architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] Each component is connected to the others through a number of exposed "ports".
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] Communication through these ports follow a given protocol depending on their purpose.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] Ports and protocols define an abstract API that can be implemented by any suitable technical means (e.g. method invocation in an object-oriented language, remote procedure calls, or web services).
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] Adapters are the glue between components and the outside world.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] They tailor the exchanges between the external world and the ports that represent the requirements of the inside of the application component.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] There can be several adapters for one port, for example, data can be provided by a user through a GUI or a command-line interface, by an automated data source, or by test scripts.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] The term "hexagonal" implies that there are 6 parts to the concept, whereas there are only 4 key areas.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] The term’s usage comes from the graphical conventions that shows the application component like a hexagonal cell.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] According to some authors, the hexagonal architecture is at the origin of the microservices architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] The onion architecture proposed by Jeffrey Palermo in 2008 is similar to the hexagonal architecture: it also externalizes the infrastructure with interfaces to ensure loose coupling between the application and the database.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] It decomposes further the application core into several concentric rings using inversion of control.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] The clean architecture proposed by Robert C.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] Martin in 2012 combines the principles of the hexagonal architecture, the onion architecture and several other variants.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] It provides additional levels of detail of the component, which are presented as concentric rings.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] It isolates adapters and interfaces (user interface, databases, external systems, devices) in the outer rings of the architecture and leaves the inner rings for use cases and entities.
[src:architecture-patterns/hexagonal-architecture-software] The clean architecture uses the principle of dependency inversion with the strict rule that dependencies shall only exist between an outer ring to an inner ring and never the contrary.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] A **message broker** (also known as an **integration broker** or **interface engine**) is an intermediary computer program module that translates a message from the formal messaging protocol of the sender to the formal messaging protocol of the receiver.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] Message brokers are elements in telecommunication or computer networks where software applications communicate by exchanging formally defined messages.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] Message brokers are a building block of message-oriented middleware (MOM) but are typically not a replacement for traditional middleware like MOM and remote procedure call (RPC).
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] A message broker is an architectural pattern for message validation, transformation, and routing.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] It mediates communication among applications, minimizing the mutual awareness that applications should have of each other in order to be able to exchange messages, effectively implementing decoupling.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] The primary purpose of a broker is to take incoming messages from applications and perform some action on them.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] Message brokers can decouple end-points, meet specific non-functional requirements, and facilitate reuse of intermediary functions.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] For example, a message broker may be used to manage a workload queue or message queue for multiple receivers, providing reliable storage, guaranteed message delivery and perhaps transaction management.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] Message brokers are generally based on one of two fundamental architectures: hub-and-spoke and message bus.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] In the first, a central server acts as the mechanism that provides integration services, whereas with the latter, the message broker is a communication backbone or distributed service that acts on the bus.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] Additionally, a more scalable multi-hub approach can be used to integrate multiple brokers.
[src:architecture-patterns/message-broker] Message brokers that are purpose built to achieve time-bounded communications with end-to-end predictability allow for the development of real-time systems that require execution predictability.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The *viewmodel* of MVVM is a value converter, meaning it is responsible for exposing (converting) the data objects from the model in such a way they can be easily managed and presented.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] In this respect, the viewmodel is more *model* than *view*, and handles most (if not all) of the view's display logic.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The viewmodel may implement a mediator pattern, organizing access to the back-end logic around the set of use cases supported by the view.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] MVVM is a variation of Martin Fowler's Presentation Model design pattern.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] MVVM is very similar to the Model-view-presenter pattern.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] It was invented by Microsoft architects Ken Cooper and Ted Peters specifically to simplify event-driven programming of user interfaces.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The pattern was incorporated into the Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF) (Microsoft's .NET graphics system) and Silverlight, WPF's Internet application derivative.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] John Gossman, a Microsoft WPF and Silverlight architect, announced MVVM on his blog in 2005.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] Model–view–viewmodel is also referred to as **model–view–binder**, especially in implementations not involving the .NET platform.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] ZK, a web application framework written in Java, and the JavaScript library KnockoutJS use model–view–binder.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] , which represents content (a data-centric approach).
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] is the structure, layout, and appearance of what a user sees on the screen.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] (properties, event callbacks, etc.) that is defined to link the view and view model.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] is an abstraction of the view exposing public properties and commands.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] , which automates communication between the view and its bound properties in the view model.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The view model has been described as a state of the data in the model.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The main difference between the view model and the Presenter in the MVP pattern is that the presenter has a reference to a view, whereas the view model does not.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] Instead, a view directly binds to properties on the view model to send and receive updates.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] Declarative data and command-binding are implicit in the MVVM pattern.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The binder frees the developer from being obliged to write boiler-plate logic to synchronize the view model and view.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] and without a binder, one would typically use MVP or MVC instead and have to write more boilerplate (or generate it with some other tool).
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] MVVM was designed to remove virtually all GUI code ("code-behind") from the view layer, by using data binding functions in WPF (Windows Presentation Foundation) to better facilitate the separation of view layer development from the rest of the pattern.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] Instead of requiring user experience (UX) developers to write GUI code, they can use the framework markup language (e.g.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] XAML) and create data bindings to the view model, which is written and maintained by application developers.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The separation of roles allows interactive designers to focus on UX needs rather than programming of business logic.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The layers of an application can thus be developed in multiple work streams for higher productivity.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] Even when a single developer works on the entire codebase, a proper separation of the view from the model is more productive, as the user interface typically changes frequently and late in the development cycle based on end-user feedback.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The MVVM pattern attempts to gain both advantages of separation of functional development provided by MVC, while leveraging the advantages of data bindings and the framework by binding data as close to the pure application model as possible.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] It uses the binder, view model, and any business layers' data-checking features to validate incoming data.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The result is that the model and framework drive as much of the operations as possible, eliminating or minimizing application logic which directly manipulates the view (e.g., code-behind).
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] John Gossman has criticized the MVVM pattern and its application in specific uses, stating that MVVM can be "overkill" when creating simple user interfaces.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] For larger applications, he believes that generalizing the viewmodel upfront can be difficult, and that large-scale data binding can lead to lower performance.
[src:architecture-patterns/model-view-viewmodel] The following are simple examples of an implementation of the MVVM pattern.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] In software engineering, a **monolithic application** is a single unified software application that is self-contained and independent from other applications, but typically lacks flexibility.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] There are advantages and disadvantages of building applications in a monolithic style of software architecture, depending on requirements.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Monolith applications are relatively simple and have a low cost but their shortcomings are lack of elasticity, fault tolerance and scalability.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Alternative styles to monolithic applications include multitier architectures, distributed computing and microservices.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Despite their popularity in recent years, monolithic applications are still a good choice for applications with small team and little complexity.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] However, once it becomes too complex, you can consider refactoring it into microservices or a distributed application.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Note that a monolithic application deployed on a single machine, may be performant enough for your current workload but it's less available, less durable, less changeable, less fine-tuned and less scalable than a well designed distributed system.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] The design philosophy is that the application is responsible not just for a particular task, but can perform every step needed to complete a particular function.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Some personal finance applications are monolithic in the sense that they help the user carry out a complete task, end to end, and are private data silos rather than parts of a larger system of applications that work together.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Some word processors are monolithic applications.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] These applications are sometimes associated with mainframe computers.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] In software engineering, a monolithic application describes a software application that is designed as a single service.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Multiple services can be desirable in certain scenarios as it can facilitate maintenance by allowing repair or replacement of parts of the application without requiring wholesale replacement.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Modularity is achieved to various extents by different modular programming approaches.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Code-based modularity allows developers to reuse and repair parts of the application, but development tools are required to perform these maintenance functions (e.g. the application may need to be recompiled).
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Object-based modularity provides the application as a collection of separate executable files that may be independently maintained and replaced without redeploying the entire application (e.g.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Microsoft's Dynamic-link library (DLL); Sun/UNIX shared object files).
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Some object messaging capabilities allow object-based applications to be distributed across multiple computers (e.g.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Microsoft's Component Object Model (COM)).
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] Service-oriented architectures use specific communication standards/protocols to communicate between modules.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] In its original use, the term "monolithic" described enormous mainframe applications with no usable modularity.
[src:architecture-patterns/monolithic-application] This, in combination with the rapid increase in computational power and therefore rapid increase in the complexity of the problems which could be tackled by software, resulted in unmaintainable systems and the "software crisis".
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] In software engineering, **multitier architecture** (often referred to as ***n*-tier architecture** or **layered architecture**) is a client–server architecture in which various levels of software architecture are physically separated.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] The most common use of multitier architecture is the **three-tier architecture**, which separates presentation, application processing and data management functions, such as in the case of Cisco's hierarchical internetworking model.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Other tiers of separation may include the service layer, business layer, data access layer, and persistence layer.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] In a strict layered system, each layer depends on the layer below it and can exist without the layers above it.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] In a relaxed layered system, a layer can also depend on *all* of the layers below it, creating additional couplings between layers.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Some multitier architectures use a hybrid approach so that some layers are strict while other layers are relaxed.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] *N*-tier architecture may also be implemented with the model–view–presenter pattern.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] The terms layer and tier are often used interchangeably, although *layer* is sometimes used to refer to a conceptual software logic structuring mechanism, while *tier* is used to refer to the physical hardware structuring mechanism for system infrastructure.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] In this usage, a three-layer solution could be deployed on a single tier, as in the case of an some database-centric architectures called RDBMS-only architecture or in personal workstations.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] The more usual convention is that the application layer (or service layer) is considered a sublayer of the business layer, typically encapsulating the application programming interface (API) definition surfacing the supported business functionality.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] The application/business layers can, in fact, be further subdivided to emphasize additional sublayers of distinct responsibility.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] For example, if the model–view–presenter pattern is used, the presenter sublayer might be used as an additional layer between the user interface layer and the business/application layer (as represented by the model sublayer).
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] If the application architecture has no explicit distinction between the business layer and the presentation layer (i.e., the presentation layer is considered part of the business layer), then a traditional client-server (two-tier) model has been implemented.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Some also identify a separate layer called the business infrastructure layer (BI), located between the business layer(s) and the infrastructure layer(s).
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] It is also sometimes called the "low-level business layer" or the "business services layer".
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] This layer is very general and can be used in several application tiers (e.g. a CurrencyConverter).
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] The infrastructure layer can be partitioned into different levels (high-level or low-level technical services).
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Developers often focus on the persistence (data access) capabilities of the infrastructure layer and therefore only talk about the persistence layer or the data access layer (instead of an infrastructure layer or technical services layer).
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] In other words, the other kind of technical services is not always explicitly thought of as part of any particular layer..
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] The Data Access layer normally contains an object known as the Data Access Object (DAO).
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] In a relaxed layered system, a layer can also depend on all of the layers below it and not merely the layer directly below it.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] The relaxed layered system has more couplings and is more difficult to change.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Three-tier architecture is a client-server software architecture pattern in which the user interface (presentation), functional process logic ("business rules"), computer data storage and data access are developed and maintained as independent modules, most often on separate platforms.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Donovan in Open Environment Corporation (OEC), a tools company he founded in Cambridge, Massachusetts..
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Apart from the usual advantages of modular software with well-defined interfaces, the three-tier architecture is intended to allow any of the three tiers to be upgraded or replaced independently in response to changes in requirements or technology.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] For example, a change of operating system in the *presentation tier* would only affect the user interface code.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] The middle tier may be multitiered itself (in which case the overall architecture is called an "*n*-tier architecture").
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] A middle dynamic content processing and generation level application server (e.g., Symfony, Spring, ASP.NET, Django, Rails, Node.js).
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] A back-end database or data store, comprising both data sets and the database management system software that manages and provides access to the data.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Data transfer between tiers is part of the architecture.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Protocols involved may include one or more of SNMP, CORBA, Java RMI, .NET Remoting, Windows Communication Foundation, sockets, UDP, web services or other standard or proprietary protocols.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Often middleware is used to connect the separate tiers.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Separate tiers often (but not necessarily) run on separate physical servers, and each tier may itself run on a cluster.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] The Application Response Measurement defines concepts and APIs for measuring performance and correlating transactions between tiers.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] Generally, the term "tiers" is used to describe physical distribution of components of a system on separate servers, computers, or networks (processing nodes).
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] A three-tier architecture then will have three processing nodes.
[src:architecture-patterns/multitier-architecture] The term "layers" refers to a logical grouping of components which may or may not be physically located on one processing node.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:architecture-patterns/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] In software engineering, **service-oriented architecture** (**SOA**) is an architectural style that focuses on discrete services instead of a monolithic design.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is a good choice for system integration.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] By consequence, it is also applied in the field of software design where services are provided to the other components by application components, through a communication protocol over a network.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] A service is a discrete unit of functionality that can be accessed remotely and acted upon and updated independently, such as retrieving a credit card statement online.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is also intended to be independent of vendors, products and technologies.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Service orientation is a way of thinking in terms of services and service-based development and the outcomes of services.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] It is a black box for its consumers, meaning the consumer does not have to be aware of the service's inner workings.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Different services can be used in conjunction as a service mesh to provide the functionality of a large software application, a principle SOA shares with modular programming.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture integrates distributed, separately maintained and deployed software components.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] It is enabled by technologies and standards that facilitate components' communication and cooperation over a network, especially over an IP network.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA is related to the idea of an API (application programming interface), an interface or communication protocol between different parts of a computer program intended to simplify the implementation and maintenance of software.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] An API can be thought of as the service, and the SOA the architecture that allows the service to operate.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Note that Service-Oriented Architecture must not be confused with Service Based Architecture as those are two different architectural styles.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] In SOA, services use protocols that describe how they pass and parse messages using description metadata.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] This metadata describes both the functional characteristics of the service and quality-of-service characteristics.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Service-oriented architecture aims to allow users to combine large chunks of functionality to form applications which are built purely from existing services and combining them in an ad hoc manner.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] A service presents a simple interface to the requester that abstracts away the underlying complexity acting as a black box.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Further users can also access these independent services without any knowledge of their internal implementation.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] The related buzzword service-orientation promotes *loose coupling* between services.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA separates functions into distinct units, or services, which developers make accessible over a network in order to allow users to combine and reuse them in the production of applications.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] These services and their corresponding consumers communicate with each other by passing data in a well-defined, shared format, or by coordinating an activity between two or more services.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] SOA can be seen as part of the continuum which ranges from the older concept of distributed computing and modular programming, through SOA, and on to practices of mashups, SaaS, and cloud computing (which some see as the offspring of SOA).
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] There are no industry standards relating to the exact composition of a service-oriented architecture, although many industry sources have published their own principles.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] documents within a given set of services.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] The relationship between services is minimized to the level that they are only aware of their existence.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services can be called from anywhere within the network that it is located no matter where it is present.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services should be designed to be long lived.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Where possible, services should avoid forcing consumers to change if they do not require new features; if you call a service today, you should be able to call the same service tomorrow.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] The services act as black boxes, that is their inner logic is hidden from the consumers.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services are independent and control the functionality they encapsulate, from a Design-time and a run-time perspective.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] Services are stateless, that is either return the requested value or give an exception hence minimizing resource use.
[src:architecture-patterns/service-oriented-architecture] A principle to ensure services have an adequate size and scope.
